# Update SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader to allow for testing of actual routing module's routes

### Relevant Package
This feature request is for @angular/router/testing.

### Description
I'm trying to implement unit tests for the routing module of my application. After reading the API docs and [issue #17902](https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/17902) I found out that [`SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader`](https://angular.io/api/router/testing/SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader) is what I need to test my lazy-loaded modules. 

However, in the discussion of that issue @burtonjc proposed a [different approach](https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/17902#issuecomment-385509867) to the one used in the API docs. He says:

> The linked docs use router.resetConfig which blows away the actual routes you are trying to test. This means you could delete your routes in source code and the tests will still pass (not ideal). We were looking to test our actual lazy route while still stubbing the lazy loading of the module.

And the implementation is like this:

```
@Component({ template: '' })
  class LazyLoadedComponent { }

  @NgModule({ declarations: [ LazyLoadedComponent ]})
  class LazyModule { }

  it('lazily navigates to "/project/create"', fakeAsync(() => {
    const loader = TestBed.get(NgModuleFactoryLoader);
    loader.stubbedModules = {
      './create-project/create-project.module#CreateProjectModule': LazyModule,
    };
    spy(loader, 'load');

    router.navigate(['project', 'create']);

    tick();
    expect(location.path()).to.equal('/project/create');
    expect(loader.load).to.have.been.calledOnce;
    expect(loader.load).to.have.been.calledWith('./create-project/create-project.module#CreateProjectModule');
  }));
```

I would like to use the suggested approach, in order to test the actual routes of my routing module instead of resetting them through `router.resetConfig()`. However, **when you specify [`LoadChildren`](https://angular.io/api/router/LoadChildren) in the routing module, the new standard way is to employ a [callback to load the module](https://angular.io/api/router/LoadChildrenCallback), and the [string path](https://angular.io/api/router/DeprecatedLoadChildren) that one can also use in [`loader.stubbedModules`](https://angular.io/api/router/testing/SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader#properties) is now deprecated. This means that there is no way to load stubbed modules using the actual routes of my routing module.**

### Solution I'd like
I would like to know if there is a way to update the implementation of `SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader` to allow for the requirements above. One should be able to pass the routing module's actual routes to `RouterTestingModule` and use `loader.stubbedModules` to specify stubbed lazy loaded modules without resetting the actual routes.


### Alternatives

- Reset routes through `router.resetConfig()`, as the docs suggest. The problem with this is that I don't know what I'm testing, since the tests end up covering only my test doubles and lose all connection to the actual code of my routing module.

- Test routing only through integration tests. I know this is an option, but I think there is room for some coverage through unit tests, especially if something like `SpyNgModuleFactoryLoader` already exists. I want to test some simple aspects of the behavior of my routing module without depending on the implementation of external routing/routed components and modules.

- Revert to the deprecated string path for `LoadChildren`. This would work, but it would be an unwanted alteration of my production code for the sake of testing. It could work as a provisional solution until an update like the proposed here can be implemented.

when applying a template, using an absolute path to templates location, it causes an error
```
...
return (tree,context){
 var source = url( __dirname + "/files" ); //using full path here causes an Error,
 var template = apply( source , [...] )
 return mergeWith(template, strategy);

//->Error: Unknown Protocol on url "[object Object]".
}
```

**use case**
if the schematics uses an external file that is not listed in collection.json to apply some rules, the template path here will be relative to the function, not the schematic function witch is wrong.

```
...
const getRule = require('./path/to/function')

return (tree,context){ 
 return getRule();
//->Error: Unknown Protocol on url "[object Object]".
}
```
```
function getRule(){
 //this is relative to the function which is in another location away from the schematic path
//the function dosen't know about the schematic location
 var source = url(  "/.files" );
 var template = apply( source , [...] )
 return mergeWith(template, strategy);
}
```
angular schematics will resolve this path relatively to the schematic location, but it is retative to the function location, then it will not find any template files.

there is a workaround, is to create a relative path between the schematic path and the template path.

```
function getRule(context){
var sourcePath = path.relative(
      context.schematic.description.path,
     path. join(__dirname, "./templates")
    )

 var source = url(  "/.files" );
...
}
```

but if the schematics started from a different drive (c:/) than the template location (D:/), then `path.relative()`
will return the absolute path which will fail again.

I reported this issue as bug rather than feature request, because it causes error in this case.
if it is incorrect label, feel free to change it.
